# How to set up a Django server? #

Step1:

Setup a python3 virtualenv.

```
#!bash

virtualenv --python=python3 .venv
source .venv/bin/activate
```

If you get the following error, then it is due to the environment settings in you terminal.

```
#!bash

[tn@localhost tmp]$ virtualenv --python=python3 .venv
Running virtualenv with interpreter /usr/bin/python3
Using base prefix '/usr'
New python executable in /home/tn/tmp/.venv/bin/python3
Also creating executable in /home/tn/tmp/.venv/bin/python
Installing setuptools, pip, wheel...
  Complete output from command /home/tn/tmp/.venv/bin/python3 - setuptools pip wheel:
  Traceback (most recent call last):
  File "<stdin>", line 23, in <module>
  File "/usr/lib/python2.7/site-packages/virtualenv_support/pip-8.1.1-py2.py3-none-any.whl/pip/__init__.py", line 215, in main
  File "/home/tn/tmp/.venv/lib64/python3.4/locale.py", line 592, in setlocale
    return _setlocale(category, locale)
locale.Error: unsupported locale setting
```

It is fixed by in your terminal on your computer removing the "LC_CTYPE" environment setting.

```
#!bash

export LC_CTYPE=""
```



Install django by pip.

```
#!bash

pip install django
```

Test if it is work.

```
#!bash

pip freeze
pip freeze > requirements.txt
```

Initialize a git repository

```
#!bash

git init
```


Initialize a django project

```
#!bash

django-admin startproject myfirstdjangoproject
tree
```


Add file to git repository, and commit it.

```
#!bash

git add .
git commit -m "Initial commit"
```

Testing your django project

```
#!bash

cd myfirstdjangoproject
python3 manage.py test
```

*About the version of python

If you install both python2 and python3 in your computer, you must start python with the version number you want to 

start up. For example:

to start python2

```
#!bash

python2
```

to start python3

```
#!bash

python3
```

You can check the version by the welcome message

Startup a django server

```
#!bash

python3 manage.py runserver
```


ssh tunneling

```
#!bash

ssh guestur@192.168.1.34 -L 8888:127.0.0.1:8000
```


To set port of the django server when startup

```
#!bash

python manage.py runserver 0.0.0.0:8000
```

